President Barack Obama has announced his intent to nominate Walter Crawford Jones as the United States Executive Director for the African Development Bank. Jones has over 20 years of experience in international development, business, law, and finance. He is currently a Senior Investment Officer at the Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) and has previously worked at the law firm Sidley & Austin and served as a Legislative Assistant for Senator Paul Sarbanes. Jones is a graduate of Princeton University, Harvard Law School, and the George Washington University School of Business and Management.

President Obama also intends to nominate Leocadia I. Zak as the Director of the United States Trade and Development Agency (USTDA). Zak has been serving as the Acting Director of USTDA since January 2009 and has been with the agency since 2000, previously serving as General Counsel. Before joining USTDA, she worked as a partner at Mintz, Levin, Cohn, Ferris, Glovsky and Popeo, P.C. Zak has taught "International Project Finance" at Boston University School of Law and Georgetown University Law Center. She holds a B.A. from Mount Holyoke College and a J.D. from Northeastern University School of Law.

In addition, President Obama has appointed Olivia Morgan to serve on the President's Committee on the Arts and the Humanities. Morgan is the former Executive Director of the Children's Health Forum and has experience in communications strategies and nonprofit development. She has also served as the Director of Federal Relations for former California Governor Gray Davis and as a national spokesperson for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. Morgan is involved with various organizations, including The New England Center for Children and A Woman's Nation.